{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CS1\n    \n      Confidence-weighted checkpoints · metacognition calibration\n      Before answering, user rates confidence 1-5. Score = accuracy × confidence. Overconfidence + wrong = bigger penalty. Humble + right = bonus. Teaches learners to know what they don't know — critical interview skill.\n      \n        Before you answer, how confident are you?\n        \n          1Guessing\n          2\n          3\n          4Fairly sure\n          5Certain\n        \n        Calibration: \"You marked 5/5 confidence on 12 questions. You got 8/12 right. You're 33% overconfident in this category.\"\n      \n      Research: meta-calibration training is 2-3x more predictive of transfer than raw accuracy.","choice":"cs1","id":null,"timestamp":1776667571414}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CS2\n    \n      Interleaved practice · mix patterns per session (not block)\n      Current approach: study Singleton Tuesday, Factory Wednesday. Research (Rohrer & Taylor) shows interleaving 5 patterns per session = 30-50% better transfer. New mode: \"Mixed drill\" — 5 random problems spanning 5 different patterns in one session. Harder, stickier.\n      \n        TONIGHT'S INTERLEAVED SESSION · 5 problems · 30 min\n        \n          Parking Lot · may use Strategy or State\n          Chat Room · may use Mediator or Observer\n          LRU Cache · may use Decorator\n          Vending Machine · may use State or Command\n          Logger · classic Singleton?\n        \n        ⚠ Problem type NOT shown — you must recognize which pattern applies. That's the point.","choice":"cs2","id":null,"timestamp":1776667580468}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CS3\n    \n      Elaborative interrogation · \"why?\" prompts\n      After each lesson, 3 \"why\" prompts force the learner to generate explanations: \"Why is Observer better than callbacks here?\" · \"Why would this fail at scale?\" · \"Why did the author choose composition over inheritance?\". Free-text answer. AI grades for depth (not correctness). Generating explanations = 2x retention.\n      \n        💡 EXPLAIN IN YOUR WORDS\n        Why does Observer scale poorly past ~1000 subscribers?\n        The broadcast becomes O(n)... subject has to iterate through all subscribers... lock contention... consider pub-sub broker instead...\n        \n          AI depth rating: 7/10\n          \n            \n          \n          solid · mentions all 3 key points","choice":"cs3","id":null,"timestamp":1776667871565}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CS4\n    \n      Productive failure · design BEFORE being taught\n      Manu Kapur research (cited in your README): learners who struggle at a problem before being taught perform 2-3x better. New format: pre-lesson design challenge. Given requirements, design it yourself (20 min). Then the lesson shows the \"canonical\" pattern. Contrast = deeper learning.\n      \n        \n          \n            Step 1 · Try it first (20 min)\n            \"Multiple subscribers need to react when stock price changes. Design it.\"\n          \n          \n            Step 2 · Reveal the canonical pattern\n            \"This is the Observer pattern. Compare yours →\"\n          \n          \n            Step 3 · What you almost got · what you missed\n            \"You nailed the broadcast idea. You missed: decoupling the Subject from concrete observer classes. Look closer...\"\n          \n        \n      \n      Toggle: \"Classic lesson\" vs \"Productive Failure lesson\" — let user pick. 2x retention for motivated learners.","choice":"cs4","id":null,"timestamp":1776667894103}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CS5\n    \n      Fading worked examples · scaffolding that disappears\n      First Observer problem: fully worked. Second: you fill in method bodies. Third: you fill in method signatures. Fourth: you define class structure. Fifth: you start from blank. Gradual handoff from scaffolded to independent.\n      \n        \n          SUPPORT\n          \n            \n            \n          \n          INDEPENDENCE\n        \n        \n          P1Fully shown\n          P2Fill methods\n          P3Fill sigs\n          P4 ●Build skeleton\n          P5Blank","choice":"cs5","id":null,"timestamp":1776667912477}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CS6\n    \n      Cold recall quiz · minutes after reading, not during\n      After a lesson, instead of embedded checkpoints, user gets a 5-minute cold quiz 10 minutes later (timed challenge, not when reading). Tests what actually stuck vs what was just recognized. Closer to interview conditions.\n      \n        🧊 Cold recall · 10 min after lesson ended\n        \n          \n            Sketch the Observer class diagram from memory\n            60s\n          \n          \n            Name 3 real-world uses\n            30s\n          \n          \n            Explain in 2 sentences why it's useful\n            45s","choice":"cs6","id":null,"timestamp":1776667924424}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CS7\n    \n      Teach-back mode · explain to an imaginary intern\n      Feynman technique. User types or records a 2-min explanation as if teaching a junior engineer. AI plays the intern — asks follow-ups. (\"Wait, why private? What if it's public?\"). Generates 3-5 probing questions. Answering them locks the concept.\n      \n        \n          🎓\n          \n            \"Singleton means one instance. We use a private constructor so nobody can call new Logger(). And a static getInstance() that makes the first one if needed.\"\n          \n        \n        \n          🧑‍💼\n          \n            Intern: \"Hmm, what happens in a multi-threaded app if two threads call getInstance() at the same time? Don't we end up with two instances?\"\n          \n        \n      \n      Can't answer = you don't really understand it. Feynman test.","choice":"cs7","id":null,"timestamp":1776667931649}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CS8\n    \n      Anti-pattern hunt · find the bug in someone's design\n      Given a UML canvas with a subtly broken design (or anti-pattern), find the issue in 5 min. Examples: \"Observer registered but never unregistered → memory leak\" · \"Singleton used as global state → hidden coupling\" · \"Inheritance where composition belongs\". Trains code review skills.\n      \n        🐛 SPOT THE BUG · 5:00 remaining\n        \n          class StockPrice {\n            subscribe(obs) { this.subs.push(obs); }\n            notify() { this.subs.forEach(o => o.update()); }\n            // missing: unsubscribe\n          }\n        \n        Your answer: \"Memory leak — no unsubscribe method...\"","choice":"cs8","id":null,"timestamp":1776667934312}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CS9\n    \n      Design debate · defend a pattern choice against AI\n      Pick a pattern. AI takes the opposite side. \"Why Observer and not Publisher-Subscriber?\" · \"Why Factory Method here? Isn't Builder better?\". 3 rounds of argument. AI grades: Were your reasons specific? Did you concede valid counterpoints? The actual interview skill.\n      \n        \n          🧑\n          I'd use Observer because multiple UI components need price updates without Subject knowing them individually.\n        \n        \n          🏛\n          But Observer has tight coupling at the subscribe-time. If a new service tomorrow wants prices, they need code access. Why not pub-sub on a message bus?\n        \n        \n          🧑\n          Your turn...","choice":"cs9","id":null,"timestamp":1776667937078}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CS10\n    \n      Daily intention · 30-second ritual at session start\n      Opening the app: \"What will you learn today?\". Quick pick: continue path / specific pattern / review / drill / exploratory. Session ends: \"Did you get there? In one sentence, what clicked?\". Builds metacognition + journaling habit.\n      \n        🌅 Today's intention\n        \n          📖 Continuepath\n          🔁 Reviewdue\n          ⏱ Drillhard\n        \n        \n          Yesterday you said: \"I wanted to get Factory Method solid.\"\n          Reflection: \"Clicked when I saw the Pizza analogy\"","choice":"cs10","id":null,"timestamp":1776667941246}
