{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CT2\n    \n      Design disasters · real war stories of what happens without the pattern\n      Each pattern has a \"war story\" page. Real incidents where missing or misusing the pattern caused production outages. Knight Capital (2012, $440M loss) as an example of missing Circuit Breaker. AWS S3 outage 2017 as cascading failure without Bulkhead.\n      \n        \n          💥\n          \n            Knight Capital · August 1, 2012\n            The $440M 45-minute trading disaster\n          \n          Circuit Breaker\n        \n        \n          A deployment left 1 of 8 servers running old code with a dormant flag re-enabled. The server sent bogus orders — thousands per second. No circuit breaker stopped the cascade. By the time humans reacted, Knight Capital had lost $440M and bankrupted itself.\n        \n        Lesson: Circuit Breaker isn't nice-to-have — it's the difference between \"weird Tuesday\" and \"company ends\".\n      \n      12-15 patterns have iconic disaster stories. Opus writes + links to post-mortems.","choice":"ct2","id":null,"timestamp":1776668826200}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CT3\n    \n      Pattern battle cards · head-to-head comparisons as collectibles\n      Pokemon-card style comparison. Observer vs Mediator. Strategy vs State. Inheritance vs Composition. Each card: stats (coupling, flexibility, complexity), special moves, weakness. Engineers collect these; great for recall + shareable.\n      \n        \n          \n          \n            BEHAVIORAL · COMMON\n            Observer\n            📢\n            Notifies many subscribers when subject changes\n            \n              Coupling\n              LOW\n              Flexibility\n              HIGH\n              Scale\n              MEDIUM\n              Weakness\n              ORDER\n            \n          \n          \n          \n            BEHAVIORAL · RARE\n            Mediator\n            🚦\n            Centralizes M-to-M object communication\n            \n              Coupling\n              MID\n              Flexibility\n              MID\n              Scale\n              LOW\n              Weakness\n              GOD\n            \n          \n        \n        VS. → which wins for chat room?","choice":"ct3","id":null,"timestamp":1776668835457}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CT4\n    \n      Choose-your-own-design-adventure · branching story per pattern\n      Interactive fiction where each decision shapes the system you build. \"You're the lead engineer. Product wants real-time stock prices in 50ms. Which do you reach for first? [Observer] [WebSocket + event bus] [Polling]\" Each choice branches. Wrong choices reveal the consequences mid-story. Right choices unlock the pattern's nuance.\n      \n        \n          Scene 3 · Wednesday, 10 AM\n          Product Manager slacks: \"The CFO dashboard is lagging 2 seconds behind trades. Fix before demo Friday.\"\n          You check the code. One StockPrice class pushes updates to 4 dashboards via direct method calls. Now we need 15 dashboards.\n        \n        \n          \n            A. Add Observer — let each dashboard subscribe\n          \n          \n            B. Move it all to a Redis pub-sub bus\n          \n          \n            C. Keep the direct calls, just add 11 more\n          \n        \n        Pick C = see cascade failure at scale. Pick A = next scene: WebSocket fan-out challenges. Pick B = \"you over-engineered. PM is angry. how do you defend?\"","choice":"ct4","id":null,"timestamp":1776668843941}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CT5\n    \n      System archaeology · \"dig through this legacy codebase\"\n      Given a fictional (or real open-source) legacy codebase. Find and identify 5 design patterns. Explain the archaeological context — why was this pattern used here, when, and what was the tradeoff at the time? Turns learning into investigation.\n      \n        🏛 DIG SITE · Legacy Order System · codebase from 2008\n        \n          public class OrderManager {\n            private static OrderManager instance;\n            public static synchronized OrderManager getInstance() {\n              // ... Singleton pattern\n            }\n          }\n        \n        \n          Question: You find Singleton used here. Explain why a 2008 engineer would reach for Singleton in this context — and what modern alternative would you use now?\n        \n        Bonus: identify 4 more patterns in this 300-line sample. Hunt them down.","choice":"ct5","id":null,"timestamp":1776668845572}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CT6\n    \n      Pattern personalities · each pattern is a character\n      Ted Chiang / Kazuo Ishiguro-style vignettes where patterns have personalities. Observer is the anxious attention-seeker. Singleton is the lone monk. Mediator is the exhausted diplomat. Circuit Breaker is the paranoid veteran. Each gets a 100-word character sketch + memorable tagline.\n      \n        \n          🧘\n          \n            Singleton\n            \"There can only be one.\"\n            \n              Singleton sits alone in the application, watched over by the runtime. Everyone thinks they know where to find him — and they do. But his solitude costs him: he can't be mocked, can't be tested in isolation, can't evolve without touching everyone. \"Being the only one sounds like power,\" he says, \"but it's mostly loneliness.\"\n            \n          \n        \n      \n      36 characters. 36 taglines. Ishiguro-grade prose from Opus. Patterns become memorable because they're human.","choice":"ct6","id":null,"timestamp":1776668850133}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CT7\n    \n      Pattern dialogues · podcast-style conversations between patterns\n      \"Observer and Pub-Sub walk into a bar...\" Two patterns debate when to use which. Written as scripts (optional audio). Observer defends itself: \"I keep subs & subject in the same process.\" Pub-Sub pushes back: \"Exactly your problem — you don't scale past one machine.\" Observer sulks. Pub-Sub buys beer.\n      \n        🎙 THE OBSERVER / PUB-SUB DEBATE · scene 1\n        \n          OBSERVER: I've served React, Angular, Vue for years. What's your deal?\n          PUB-SUB: I serve 15 microservices at once. You couldn't keep up past 1,000 subscribers.\n          OBSERVER: (sulking) I never claimed to. That's what message brokers are for.\n          PUB-SUB: So admit it — you're in-memory only.\n          OBSERVER: And you need infrastructure! Kafka. RabbitMQ. Configs. I'm 3 classes in your app.\n          PUB-SUB: (pauses, sips) Fair.\n        \n      \n      20-30 dialogues covering the classic \"confused-with\" pairs. Shareable. Memorable. Fun.","choice":"ct7","id":null,"timestamp":1776668853364}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"CT9\n    \n      Pattern FAQ · questions engineers actually ask on Stack Overflow\n      Mine Stack Overflow for top 10 questions per pattern — questions real engineers got stuck on. Present as lesson section: \"Questions you'll probably ask.\" Instead of anticipating what you think, show what the hive mind actually stumbled over.\n      \n        ❓ REAL QUESTIONS · TOP 5 FROM STACK OVERFLOW\n        \n          \n            \"Why is double-checked locking broken in Java before 1.5?\"\n            1.2k upvotes · memory model & volatile deep-dive\n          \n          \n            \"Singleton vs static class — which one to use?\"\n            800 upvotes · classic mistake\n          \n          \n            \"How do you unit test a Singleton?\"\n            650 upvotes · the everybody-hates-it problem\n          \n          \n            \"Thread-safe Singleton in Python — is __init__ enough?\"\n            420 upvotes · language-specific nuance\n          \n        \n      \n      Manual curation + AI synthesis. ~10 questions × 36 patterns = 360 FAQs. High-SEO content.","choice":"ct9","id":null,"timestamp":1776668875368}
